				 Winds blow in favour of Suzlon
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 Tanti: Good show																								Mumbai, Oct. 23: Suzlon Energy Ltd has posted a 68 per cent rise in consolidated net profit at Rs 398 crore for the quarter ended September 30, 2007, against Rs 237 crore for the corresponding quarter a year ago. The company today proposed a stock split in the ratio of 5:1, dividing each share of face value of Rs 10 into five units of Rs 2.																								The company said the stock split would increase the liquidity of the shares and draw more investors.																								The company recorded a 74 per cent surge in consolidated revenues at Rs 3,641 crore during the quarter. Overseas operations accounted for about 61 per cent of the companys total sales during the period at Rs 2,232 crore. 																								We have achieved the highest ever sales and profits at the consolidated level for any quarter. We are planning new initiatives. We will scale up our earlier plans to fulfil our global ambitions. We are committed to working towards mitigation of the climate crisis. Our rapid growth clearly shows that the world is acting to meet this challenge, said Tulsi R. Tanti, chairman and managing director of Suzlon.																								The company also plans to list its Belgium-based wholly owned subsidiary Hansen Transmissions International NV. Hansen on the London Stock Exchange. 
